<p>Denote includes the option of adding different directories, so this now makes sense:</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4"><code class="language-lisp" data-lang="lisp">(<span style="color:#66d9ef">setq</span> denote-directory
      (<span style="color:#66d9ef">if</span> (<span style="color:#a6e22e">eq</span> system-type <span style="color:#e6db74">&#39;gnu/linux</span>)          <span style="color:#75715e">; If I&#39;m using Linux, include the private folder.</span>
          (<span style="color:#a6e22e">list</span> (expand-file-name <span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;~/Sync/Notes&#34;</span>)
                (expand-file-name <span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;~/Documents/private&#34;</span>))
        (<span style="color:#a6e22e">list</span> (expand-file-name <span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;~/Sync/Notes&#34;</span>)))) <span style="color:#75715e">; If I&#39;m using anything else (macOS) just Notes.</span>

(<span style="color:#66d9ef">setq</span> denote-excluded-directories-regexp <span style="color:#e6db74">&#34;data&#34;</span>) <span style="color:#75715e">; the data folder (with attachments) is excluded.</span>
</code></pre></div><p>I have <a href="https://taonaw.com/2025/07/31/denote-with-a-different-root.html">a private folder for Denote notes on Linux only</a>. I used to only sync my <code>Sync/Notes</code> folder, which includes my informational notes and blog posts, but that means I&rsquo;m missing out on Denote&rsquo;s abilities in my private folder, which is slowly increasing in size. This solves this problem.</p>
<p>There&rsquo;s no need to list the data folder (which includes my attachments, mostly in file formats that are not Denote&rsquo;s format), so that&rsquo;s why the exclusion is there.</p>
